So steering is found and delivered. But then `try_deliver_follow_up` isn't called because `try_deliver_steering` returns true early. That's by design - it returns true if it delivered something.

But wait - after delivering one steering message, the function returns and `try_deliver_follow_up` is never called! This is a bug in my implementation. Let me look at the original `deliver_queued` logic:

```rust
pub(crate) fn deliver_queued(&mut self) {
    if self.message_queue.is_empty() {
        return;
    }
    if self.try_deliver_steering() {
        return;  // <-- Early return!
    }
    self.try_deliver_follow_up();  // Never reached if steering delivered
}
```

The original logic was:- Try to deliver steering- If steering was delivered, return early (don't deliver follow-up yet)
- Otherwise try to deliver follow-up

This makes sense for sequential delivery - you deliver one thing at a time. But for "All" mode, we want to batch all messages together. The issue is that we can't batch if we return early.

I need to modify the logic so that when steering is delivered in "All" mode, we also deliver follow-ups in "All" mode. Let me fix this:

